g more than forty years, Ellis has made some of the most spectacular discoveries in modern cosmology. He has traveled the world to conduct observations in locales as beautiful and remote as the Australian outback, the Canary Islands, Hawaii, and the Chilean desert. In this book, he brings to life a golden age of astronomy, describing the triumphs and the technical setbacks, the rivalries with competing teams, and the perennial challenge of cloudy nights. Ellis reveals the astonishing progress we have made in building ever larger and more powerful telescopes, and provides a tantalizing glimpse of cosmic dawn.Stunningly illustrated with a wealth of dramatic photos, When Galaxies Were Born is a bold scientific adventure enlivened by personal insights and anecdotes that enable readers to share in the thrill of discovery at the frontiers of astronomy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAstronomyxObservations. 0aAstronomy-Observations. 0aCosmology. 0aGalaxiesxFormation. 0aGalaxies-Formation. 7aSCIENCE / Astronomy.2bisacsh  aAbsorption band.  aAge of the universe.  aAmerican Astronomical Society.  aAnglo-Australian Telescope.  aAstronomer.  aAstronomy.  aAstrophysics.  aAutomation.  aBritish Astronomical Association.  aCERN.  aCalifornia Institute of Technology.  aChronology of the universe.  aCosmic distance ladder.  aCosmic dust.  aCosmos Club.  aDiffusion.  aEarth's orbit.  aEcliptic.  aElementary particle.  aEnergy transition.  aExploration.  aFlavour (particle physics).  aGalaxy cluster.  aGalaxy.  aGeneral relativity.  aGravitational lens.  aGravity.  aHawaii.  aHerzberg Institute of Astrophysics.  aHubble Space Telescope.  aHydrogen atom.  aHydrogen spectral series.  aInstitute for Astronomy.  aInternational Astronomical Union.  aInterstella